# Documentation

## Governance

Subordinate to `docs/architecture/ai-constitution.md`. Documentation updates are workflow Step 10.

| Document | Path |
|----------|------|
| AI Constitution | `docs/architecture/ai-constitution.md` |
| Workflow | `.cursor/rules/workflow.mdc` |
| Universal agent instructions | `AGENTS.md` |
| Project context skill | `.claude/skills/project-context/SKILL.md` |
| Project vision | `docs/architecture/project-vision.md` |

## Purpose

Maintain clear, accurate documentation for draft.io's architecture, game design, and module conventions. Docs live in `docs/` and colocated `README.md` files. Documentation describes **intent and rules** — it is not a substitute for self-documenting code.

## Required Behavior

### Documentation Structure

```
docs/
├── architecture/       # System design, module interactions, audits
├── game-design/        # Game rules: players, formations, draft, simulation
└── decisions/          # ADRs (Architecture Decision Records)
```

### Document Types

| Type | Location | When to write |
|------|----------|---------------|
| Architecture overview | `docs/architecture/` | New modules, cross-cutting concerns |
| Game design spec | `docs/game-design/` | New game mechanics or rule changes |
| ADR | `docs/decisions/NNN-title.md` | Significant technical decisions |
| Module guide | `apps/backend/src/modules/README.md` | Module structure conventions |
| Package/app README | Colocated | Setup, scripts, local dev |

### ADR Format

Each ADR in `docs/decisions/` follows:

```markdown
# NNN: Title

## Status
Accepted | Proposed | Deprecated

## Context
Why this decision is needed.

## Decision
What was decided.

## Consequences
Positive and negative outcomes.
```

### Game Design Docs

- State **current implementation status** explicitly (`Implemented`, `Partial`, `Not implemented`).
- Separate **rules** (what the game does) from **open questions** (undecided).
- Reference domain modules by name (`players`, `teams`, `simulation`).
- Include input/output tables for systems like match simulation and chemistry.

### README Files

- Start with one-sentence purpose.
- Include prerequisites (Node 20+, pnpm 9+).
- List available scripts with brief descriptions.
- Link to deeper docs rather than duplicating architecture content.
- Keep setup steps tested and current.

### Accuracy

- Update docs when implementation status changes (e.g., placeholder → implemented).
- Mark future/planned features clearly — don't document them as if they exist.
- Cross-reference related docs (architecture overview ↔ game design ↔ ADRs).

### Writing Style

- Use complete sentences and active voice.
- Prefer tables and diagrams (ASCII or mermaid) for complex flows.
- Use consistent terminology: "aggregate", "use case", "value object", "starting eleven".
- Code examples in docs should match actual project patterns (reference `players/` module).

## Forbidden Patterns

- Documenting aspirational features without a "Current State" section.
- Duplicating the same architecture explanation in multiple READMEs.
- Stale setup instructions (wrong ports, missing env vars).
- Documenting internal implementation details that change frequently.
- Using docs to specify behavior that contradicts domain code.
- Empty placeholder sections ("TBD" everywhere with no context).
- Committing generated build artifacts documentation.

## Good Examples

```markdown
# Match Simulation

## Purpose
Match simulation resolves competitive encounters between two teams.

## Rules

### Current State
- **Not implemented.** The `simulation` module is a placeholder.
- Team and player domain structures exist to support future inputs.

### Planned Inputs
| Input | Source |
|-------|--------|
| Team A starting eleven | `Team.startingEleven` |
| Formation | `Team.formationCode` |
```

```markdown
# 002: Clean Architecture

## Status
Accepted

## Context
The backend must support multiple game domains with testable business logic.

## Decision
Adopt Clean Architecture with four layers per bounded context module.

## Consequences
- Positive: Domain logic is framework-agnostic and unit-testable.
- Negative: More boilerplate than a simple CRUD approach.
```

## Bad Examples

```markdown
# Players Module

Players are managed via the API. Use Prisma to create players.
POST /players with JSON body.
```

```markdown
# Simulation

The simulation engine runs tick-based physics with full play-by-play.
(When module is still an empty placeholder)
```

```markdown
# Setup

Run npm install && npm start
(When project uses pnpm and separate backend/frontend dev scripts)
```

## Checklist

- [ ] Document has a clear Purpose section at the top
- [ ] Implementation status is stated honestly (implemented vs planned)
- [ ] Game rules separated from open questions
- [ ] ADRs follow the standard format with status and consequences
- [ ] README includes working setup steps and script references
- [ ] Terminology matches codebase conventions
- [ ] Cross-references link to related docs instead of duplicating content
- [ ] Docs updated alongside code changes that affect described behavior
